wing%20months%2C%20sightings%20have%20grown%2C%20Stephen%20Hummel%2C%20an%20astronomer%20at%20McDonald%20Observatory%2C%20told%20Spaceweather.com.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe%20are%20seeing%202%20to%205%20of%20them%20each%20month%2C%26quot%3B%20Hummel%20told%20Spaceweather.com.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOne%20such%20case%20of%20these%20atmospheric%20phenomena%20was%20observed%20in%20July%20after%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspacex-launch-hole-ionosphere-earth-atmosphere-physicist-2023-7%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ESpaceX%20launched%20its%20Falcon%209%20rocket%3C%2Fa%3E%20from%20a%20base%20in%20California.%20Previous%20instances%20have%20been%20recorded%20in%202017%20and%202018.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3ESpaceX%20isn't%20the%20first%20to%20punch%20a%20harmless%20hole%20in%20the%20atmosphere%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20a%20hole%20in%20the%20atmosphere%20sounds%20dramatic%2C%20this%20phenomenon%20is%20temporary%20and%20harmless%20to%20life%20on%20Earth%2C%20Jeffrey%20Baumgardner%2C%20a%20senior%20research%20scientist%20at%20the%20Center%20for%20Space%20Physics%20at%20Boston%20University%2C%20told%20Business%20Insider.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHe%20explained%20that%20scientists%20have%20been%20studying%20ionospheric%20holes%20for%20decades.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BDuring%20the%20beginning%20of%20the%20space%20age%20when%20they%20started%20launching%20rockets%2C%20through%20the%20Earth's%20atmosphere%20into%20space%2C%20it%20was%20observed%20that%20they%20made%20a%20disturbance%20in%20the%20atmosphere%2C%26quot%3B%20Baumgardner%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20fact%2C%20the%20holes%20a%20rocket%20burns%20into%20the%20ionosphere%20are%20basically%20just%20a%20concentrated%20version%20of%20what%20naturally%20happens%20across%20the%20entire%20globe%2C%20every%20night%2C%20Baumgardner%20explained.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20May%201973%2C%20researchers%20recorded%20a%20%26quot%3Blarge-scale%20hole%26quot%3B%20in%20the%20ionosphere%20caused%20by%20NASA's%20launch%20of%20the%20Saturn%20V%20Rocket%20from%20the%20Kennedy%20Space%20Center%20in%20Florida%2C%20according%20to%20a%20study%20published%20in%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.science.org%2Fdoi%2F10.1126%2Fscience.187.4174.343%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EScience%20Magazine%3C%2Fa%3E.%20The%20impacts%20were%20seen%201%2C000%20km%20or%20about%20620%20miles%20from%20the%20%26quot%3Bburning%20engines%26quot%3B%20of%20the%20rocket.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EThe%20ionosphere%20is%20constantly%20in%20flux%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EEach%20day%2C%20the%20ionosphere%20is%20created%20when%20the%20sun's%20rays%20hit%20a%20part%20of%20our%20atmosphere%20about%20185%20miles%20above%20Earth%2C%20exciting%20mostly%20oxygen%20and%20nitrogen%20atoms%2C%20Baumgardner%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThen%2C%20each%20night%2C%20when%20the%20sun's%20rays%20are%20absent%2C%20those%20excited%20atoms%20recombine%20with%20molecules%20in%20the%20ionosphere.%20As%20a%20result%2C%20the%20ionosphere%20naturally%20decays%20away.%20This%20recombination%20creates%20a%20faint%20emission%20of%20light%20%E2%80%94%20an%20effect%20called%20airglow%20%E2%80%94%20Baumgardner%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESimilarly%2C%20when%20a%20rocket%20enters%20the%20ionosphere%2C%20the%20chemicals%20in%20its%20exhaust%2C%20like%20carbon%20dioxide%20and%20water%20vapor%2C%20recombine%20with%20those%20excited%20oxygen%20and%20nitrogen%20atoms%20more%20rapidly%2C%20and%20that%20recombination%20can%20show%20up%20as%20red%20blobs%20in%20the%20sky%2C%20Baumgardner%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20just%20about%20any%20rocket%20may%20have%20this%20effect%20on%20the%20ionosphere%2C%20SpaceX%20rockets'%20impact%20is%20two-fold%3A%20First%2C%20when%20the%20rocket%20flies%20to%20space%20and%20then%2C%20again%2C%20when%20the%20rocket%20descends%20toward%20Earth.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20example%2C%20the%20bright%20spherical%20balls%20that%20astronomers%20at%20McDonald%20Observatory%20are%20witnessing%20are%20from%20Falcon%209%20boosters%20firing%20their%20engines%20to%20return%20to%20Earth%2C%20per%20Spaceweather.com.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EHow%20ionospheric%20holes%20could%20disrupt%20astronomical%20observations%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20bright%20red%20blobs%20don't%20last%20long.%20Some%20of%20the%20recent%20ones%20that%20have%20appeared%20over%20Texas%20last%20for%20one%20to%20two%20minutes%2C%20Baumgardner%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20if%20an%20astronomer%20just%20so%20happens%20to%20aim%20a%20telescope%20at%20the%20same%20part%20of%20the%20sky%20where%20one%20of%20these%20blobs%20appears%2C%20it%20could%20mean%20a%20very%20bad%20day%20for%20an%20astronomer.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20could%20ruin%20somebody's%20time%20on%20a%20telescope%2C%26quot%3B%20Baumgardner%20said.%20%26quot%3BThey%20sometimes%20wait%20a%20year%20to%20get%20two%20or%20three%20nights%20on%20telescopes.%20So%20that%20would%20be%20a%20bad%20outcome%20for%20them%20if%20that%20actually%20happened.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESpaceX%20announced%20earlier%20this%20year%20that%20the%20company%20plans%20to%20launch%20a%20record%20144%20rockets%20to%20ramp%20up%20its%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspacex-plans-record-rocket-launches-starlink-cell-service-elon-musk-2023-10%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EStarlink%20satellite%20internet%20service%3C%2Fa%3E.%20This%20may%20cause%20an%20issue%20for%20ground-based%20astronomers%20if%20SpaceX%20utilizes%20its%20reusable%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Felon-musk-spacex-goal-60-falcon-rocket-launches-this-year-2022-3%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EFalcon%209%20rocket%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20which%20could%20tear%20holes%20in%20the%20atmosphere%20not%20only%20on%20the%20way%20to%20space%20but%20when%20it%20returns%20to%20Earth.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESpaceX%20did%20not%20respond%20to%20Business%20Insider's%20request%20for%20comment.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fspacex-r